Setup and Context¶

Introduction¶

Dr Ignaz Semmelweis was a Hungarian physician born in 1818 who worked in the Vienna General Hospital. In the past people thought of illness as caused by "bad air" or evil spirits. But in the 1800s Doctors started looking more at anatomy, doing autopsies and started making arguments based on data. Dr Semmelweis suspected that something was going wrong with the procedures at Vienna General Hospital. Semmelweis wanted to figure out why so many women in maternity wards were dying from childbed fever (i.e., puerperal fever).

Today you will become Dr Semmelweis. This is your office . You will step into Dr Semmelweis' shoes and analyse the same data collected from 1841 to 1849.

The Data Source¶

Dr Semmelweis published his research in 1861. I found the scanned pages of the full text with the original tables in German, but an excellent English translation can be found here.

The Effect of Handwashing¶

Dr Semmelweis made handwashing obligatory in the summer of 1947. In fact, he ordered people to wash their hands with clorine (instead of water).

In [23]:
# Date when handwashing was made mandatory
handwashing_start = pd.to_datetime('1847-06-01')

Challenge:

  • Calculate the average death rate after June 1947.

In [25]:
handwash_date = pd.to_datetime("1847-06-01")
before_handwash = df_monthly[df_monthly["date"] < handwash_date]
after_handwash = df_monthly[df_monthly["date"] >= handwash_date]
print(f"The Average death rate prior to June 1847 is {(before_handwash['pct_deaths'].mean())*100:.3}%.")

In [31]:
fig = px.histogram(df_monthly,
             x="pct_deaths",
             color='handwashing_status',
             histnorm='percent',
             barmode='overlay',
             opacity=0.6,
             nbins=30,
             marginal='box')

fig.update_layout(title="Percentage of Deaths monthly distribution",
                  yaxis_title="Count")

# Here, We are creating histogram to visualize the distribution of death percentage monthly before and after
# the handwashing.
# color argument is providing the color to the bars of the histogram based on the "handwashing_status" column.
# opacity argument is used to set the transparency of the histogram bars.
# nbins argument is used to set the number of bins on the histogram.
# barmode argument set to "overlay" is used to put the bars of histogram on top of each other.
# It makes easy to compare two datasets(before_handwash and after_handwash).
# histnorm argument set to "percent" is used to set the y-axis values as percentages rather than numbers.
# As, the records in dataset of after_handwash is lesser than the before_handwash.
# That's why if we consider only numbers then, the histogram becomes completely different.
# The count values of before_handwash will be more.

Use a Kernel Density Estimate (KDE) to visualise a smooth distribution¶

Challenge: Use Seaborn's .kdeplot() to create two kernel density estimates of the pct_deaths, one for before handwashing and one for after.

  • Use the shade parameter to give your two distributions different colours.
  • What weakness in the chart do you see when you just use the default parameters?
  • Use the clip parameter to address the problem.
In [32]:
# By default the distribution estimate includes a negative death rate!
plt.figure(dpi=200)
sns.kdeplot(before_handwash.pct_deaths, fill=True)
sns.kdeplot(after_handwash.pct_deaths, fill=True)
plt.title('Est. Distribution of Monthly Death Rate Before and After Handwashing')
plt.show()

# KDE is a method that is used to estimate and visualise the underlying probability distibution of a dateset.
# For example:- Imagine you have a set of data points, like ages of people in a group. KDE helps you answer
# questions like "What's the most likely age of a person in this group?" in a smooth and intuitive way.
# First, we smooth the data, to smooth it, we apply the kernel function at each data point.
# Then, KDE curve is constructed by summing all the individual kernel functions.
# THe shape of the curve represents the most likely value in the dataset. The peak of the curve
# represents the most likely value and valley(going downside) represents the less likely value.
# Kernel is a mathematical function
# In this code, we are creating KDE plot for before_handwash and after_handwash.
# In order to visualise the distribution of monthly death rate between both of the datasets.
# sns.kdeplot() is used to create kde plot.
# It takes the data that needs to be visualized.
# fill parameter refers to the area that is under kde curve, should be shaded.
In [33]:
# By default the distribution estimate includes a negative death rate!
plt.figure(dpi=200)
sns.kdeplot(before_handwash.pct_deaths, fill=True, clip=(0, 1))
sns.kdeplot(after_handwash.pct_deaths, fill=True, clip=(0, 1))
plt.title('Est. Distribution of Monthly Death Rate Before and After Handwashing')
plt.xlim(0, 0.40)
plt.show()

# Clip argument is used to limit the range of values when creating KDE plot.

Use a T-Test to Show Statistical Significance¶

Challenge: Use a t-test to determine if the differences in the means are statistically significant or purely due to chance.

If the p-value is less than 1% then we can be 99% certain that handwashing has made a difference to the average monthly death rate.

  • Import stats from scipy
  • Use the .ttest_ind() function to calculate the t-statistic and the p-value
  • Is the difference in the average proportion of monthly deaths statistically significant at the 99% level?
In [34]:
t_statistic, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(before_handwash["pct_deaths"], after_handwash["pct_deaths"])
print(f"The t_statistic is {t_statistic:.3}")
print(f"The p-value is {p_value:.10f}")

# As, we have done before, we find the difference between the mean/average of pct_deaths of both of the datasets(before and after handwash).
# Here, we are running a t-test to check whether the difference holds significance or just a purely due to chance.
# t-statistics is a numerical value that measures the difference between the mean of each group.
# If the t-statistics's value is higher then difference is strong and implies both of the means are apart of each other.
# p-value is a probability value that tells you the likelihood of obtaining the observed difference between the mean of both of the groups.
# If the p-value is lower then it rejects null-hypothesis(means no difference between the mean of both of the groups.)
# Here our p-value is less than 1% means that handwashing was definitely effective in preventing deaths.

The t_statistic is 5.51
The p-value is 0.0000002985
